programme.title: Allman Brothers
programme.desc: The Allman Brothers Band combined deeply Southern strains of music — blues, country, and gospel — with boisterous rock & roll and their jazzy, jam-oriented style. Thus they created the "New South" sound, drafting a template to be used for decades by everyone from Lynyrd Skynyrd and the Marshall Tucker Band to My Morning Jacket and the Drive-By Truckers.

programme.title: Rod Stewart
programme.desc: Roderick David Stewart was born in Highgate North London as the Second World war was coming to a close. His neighbourhood was bombed just 30 minutes before his birth, giving him the feeling that he almost didn't make it into the world. One of Rod's earliest exposures to music was with the family gatherings around the piano in which they would sing songs by the 30s baritone singer, Al Jolson. The young Rod was also caught up in the wake of Rock and Roll music that swept 50s Britain. Rod developed a love of Otis Redding and Sam Cooke and took to the Blues circuit with his first band The Dimensions. However Rod lost vocal duties to Jimmy Powell and soon left the group but fate intervened in the form of singer Long John Baldry. Baldry brought Stewart into his band The Hoochie Coochie Men, but like many of Rod's musical projects in the mid 60s it was short lived. However Baldry and Stewart were soon back together as part of Steam Packet along with Julie Driscoll. Rod had embraced the Mod look by this stage and the nickname Rod the Mod began to stick as his recognition grew. After leaving Steam Packet Rod was quickly picked up by former Yard Birds guitarist Jeff Beck. Rod had been a fan of The Yard Birds and this opportunity not only gave him a chance to sing with a hero, but also tour extensively across the US in the late 60s. Whilst on tour with Jeff Beck, Rod met guitarist Ronnie Wood, the two remained friends and when the Jeff Beck group disbanded, Rod and Ronnie became part of a new band that would be key to the success of both of their careers, Faces Despite his success with Faces, Rod released his own debut solo album An Old Raincoat Won't Ever Let You Down. The bulk of which was recorded during his time in the Jeff Beck group Things would change dramatically for Stewart as a solo artist with the release of his third solo album 1971's Every Picture Tells A Story. The album would make him the first solo artist to achieve the number 1 position in both the US and the UK. And would give him his first smash hit single Maggie May Featuring archive material, music videos “Maggie May” “In The Morning” and, exclusive insights from music critics and journalists Michael Bonner (Uncut Magazine), Hamish MacBain (Shortlist), John Aizlewood (Evening Standard) Rock Legends Rod Stewart tells the story of one of Britain's enduring rock stars.

programme.title: Daryl Hall & John Oates
programme.sub-title: Live at The Sydney Entertainment Centre
programme.desc: When Daryl Hall and John Oates took to the stage at Sydney's Entertainment Centre as the iconic bass line of ‘Maneater' began to play, the fans knew they were in for a treat. This duo may have been opening concerts with that irresistibly smooth number for years, but it never seems to lose its magic, and the crowd – an eclectic mix of teens and baby boomers alike – lapped it up. Daryl Hall and John Oates wisely reunited a few years ago after a string of solo projects, and although Oates no longer sports his signature ‘tache, they put on the kind of show that makes it hard to believe they even considered going their separate ways. Earworms like ‘I Can't Go For That', ‘Out Of Touch' and ‘Kiss On My List' were surefire reminders that these guys are absolute hit machines, and their catchy synth-soul classics probably deserve to permeate the airwaves as much today as they did decades ago. These Philly crooners still have it in bucket-loads, so this show should have everyone from diehard Daryl Hall and John Oates fans to kids of the 80's groovin' along in no time.

programme.title: Adrien Perruchon, Symfonieorkest Vlaanderen & Josef Špaček
programme.sub-title: Works by Ravel, Lalo, Ginastera a. o.
programme.desc: French conductor Adrien Perruchon and the Flanders Symphony Orchestra take us on a musical journey to Argentine, Spain, and Mexico, in this March 1, 2017 concert performance at Concertgebouw Brugge in Belgium. The program opens with Édouard Lalo's Spanish Symphony for violin and orchestra, Op. 21, featuring Czech violinist Josef Špaček as the soloist. This is followed by Mathias Coppens' Music for Orchestra, Op. 12. The program continues with Alberto Ginastera's Dances from Estancia, Op. 8a, and Aaron Copland's El Salón México. Also on the program is Maurice Ravel's famous Boléro. The program comes to a close with Arturo Márquez's Danzón No. 2.

programme.title: Evgeny Kissin, Nikolai Demidenko, Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra & Antoni Wit
programme.desc: Antoni Wit conducts the Warsaw Philharmonic Orchestra in performances of Chopin's Piano Concertos No. 1, Op. 11 and No. 2, Op. 21. Soloists are Nikolai Demidenko and Evgeny Kissin. After performing the first concerto, Demidenko encores with Chopin's Mazurka Op. 17/4. Kissin closes the concert with Chopin's Etude Op. 10/12 and the Waltz in E minor, Op. post. This concert was part of the celebration of Chopin's 200th anniversary in 2010. Chopin composed the second concerto one year before the Concerto No. 1 and completed both works at the age of 20, before leaving his home country Poland and moving to Paris.

programme.title: Herbert Blomstedt & Gewandhausorchester Leipzig
programme.sub-title: Symphonies in D by Mozart and Voríšek
programme.desc: Conductor Herbert Blomstedt and the Gewandhausorchester take us on a musical journey to the Czech Republic in this 2020 concert from Leipzig's Gewandhaus. The program opens with Bohemian composer Jan Václav Hugo Voríšek's Symphony in D major, Op. 23 (1821). Although the composition – Voríšek's only symphony – was never performed during the composer's lifetime, it has become one of his most-performed works today. Also on the program is Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's Symphony No. 38 in D major, K. 504. This work, which premiered while Mozart was visiting Prague in 1787, is often referred to as the ‘Prague Symphony'.

programme.title: Ivan Fischer, Budapest Festival Orchestra & Richard Goode
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphonies and Piano Concerto No. 4
programme.desc: Iván Fischer leads his Budapest Festival Orchestra (BFO) in a concert program dedicated to the music of Ludwig van Beethoven. The program opens with the composer's Symphony No. 1 in C major, Op. 21. Afterward, Fischer conducts Beethoven's Piano Concerto No. 4 in G major, Op. 58, in which Richard Goode features as the soloist. The acclaimed American pianist (1943) is known for his interpretations of the Beethoven repertoire. Goode recorded all five Beethoven piano concertos with the BFO and Fischer, earning him exceptional critical acclaim and a Grammy Award nomination. As an encore, Goode performs the Sarabande from J. S. Bach's Partita in B-flat major, BWV 825. The program closes with Beethoven's famous Symphony No. 5 in C minor, Op. 67. This performance was recorded at the Béla Bartók National Concert Hall in Budapest, Hungary, on January 29, 2017.

programme.title: Wanderlust
programme.sub-title: Earth And Stars III — A Sustainable Future by Climate Art Collection
programme.desc: Earth And Stars E3: A Sustainable Future presented by Climate Art Collection — This collection addresses climate change awareness through art, in collaboration with the Climate Art Collection, the largest collection of climate change-related artworks in the world. It highlights the Climate Art Collection's mission to support climate initiatives through art and make scientific concepts more accessible.

programme.title: Wanderlust
programme.desc: Earth And Stars E2: Earth Day — A beautiful, artistic tribute to our planet, from splendid skyscapes and depictions of our solar system, to sprawling forests, snow-capped mountains, and marine animals. The range of styles explore our connection to the vast and vivid universe.

programme.title: Wanderlust
programme.desc: Urban Landscapes E1 — Discover the artistic pulse that beats within the soul of the city! Captivating cityscapes and skylines, alive with movement and bold architectural beauty, showcase the essence of modern life and exude the electric energy through the vibrant hues.

programme.title: Winter Visions
programme.desc: Winter Visions — Step into a world where each artwork transports viewers to a whimsical realm where snowflakes dance & twinkling lights & laughter fills the air. The music in sets a groovy and euphoric holiday tone featuring flutes, bells, strings, and synth pads.

programme.title: New Year Cheer: White SIlver and Gold
programme.desc: New Year Cheer: White SIlver and Gold E3 — Celebrate the dawn of a sparkling New Year with elegant strokes of white, silver, and gold. The artwork create a harmonious symphony of sophistication and hope, radiating a sense of renewal and opulence.

programme.title: Shades of Color: Seasonal Shades of White Silver & Gold
programme.desc: Shades of Color: Seasonal Shades of White Silver & Gold E1 — A stunning collection of white, silver, and gold artworks, showcasing elegance and refinement through minimalist and metallic tones.
